    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"416301\">@Zhen Lin Low</span> oh yeah I see, you need some compatibility between limits and colimits as well?</p>",
        "id": 253360858,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1631680270
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You could say that. Or you could just directly specify hypotheses on the subobject posets.</p>",
        "id": 253361846,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1631681307
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right but I'm looking for conditions on C</p>",
        "id": 253436663,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1631720858
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A condition on the subobject posets of C is a condition on C...</p>",
        "id": 253453676,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1631726363
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I know what you mean.  For unions (including the empty union, i.e. the bottom element) what you need are coproducts and images.  You probably want them to be pullback-stable, in which case you get a coherent category.</p>",
        "id": 253453984,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1631726473
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To make it a Heyting category, it suffices to be locally cartesian closed.</p>",
        "id": 253454029,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1631726489
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hey, I think something like this would be addressed in <em>Boolean and Classical Restriction Categories</em> by Cockett and Manes. I haven't checked the paper in ages, but there should be a characterization of when a class of monics <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{M}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">M</span></span></span></span> in a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> gives rise to a boolean/classical restriction categories (which, if I remember correctly, correspond to the sorts of lattices you're talking about).</p>\n<p>Edit: I don't have access to a university library account at the moment, so I can only work off of a pretty vague memory and the abstract of the paper.</p>",
        "id": 253456578,
        "sender_full_name": "Ben MacAdam",
        "timestamp": 1631727568
    }
]